<br>
* What was Slipstream like when you joined?<br>
<br>
I joined at the end of July, 2000.  I came from hercules fandom and Andi sent me to SS.  At that time there was some adjusting to all the different boards, the mixing of herc and scifi fandom and getting to know some of the people involved with the show (like Ashley Edward Miller and Zack Stentz and Robert Hewitt Wolfe).  I think the &quot;tone&quot; of the place was very optimistic and also filled with anticipation.  The show hadn't aired yet, Sorbo fans were anxious to see their hero in a new venue, Trek fans and especially DS9 fans were thrilled that Robert was the head writer.  At that time, although we had moderators by and large it was a less is more kind of moderation.  Trolls were either ignored, run or treated to donut parties and we didn't really have a big problem.  When the show started the atmosphere was even more positively charged because at SS it was mostly very well received and we had the added bonus of getting to talk about eps with Ash, Zack and Robert and to a lesser extent Ethlie Ann Vare and Paul Wodmandese (science advisor).  It was very good.  And very much reflective of attitudes toward the show.  This is important to keep in mind.<br>
<br>
* Did it change? If so, in which ways did it change?<br>
<br>
Yes it changed.  For one thing, Christian brought Lisa to the board and let's just say that I'm sorry I was right in my prediction that she and her rules would be the death of that board. Her rules were a curious and frustrating mixture of rigidity that also did not effectively handle problems (like trolls).  <br>
The other big changes had to do with the show.  As season two began (and we were all so thrilled for that and really looking forward to it), some people expressed concerns that Andromeda would be &quot;Tribunized&quot; in the way that Earth Final Conflict was.  Most of us didn't think so but it turns out that this guy was right on the money from day one.  Word of Trance losing her tail got out and there was a great deal of angst over that.  And Slipstream reflected that angst just as intensely as it had reflected the optimism and happy anticipation of earlier times.  And then we found out that Robert had been fired and all hell broke loose.  <br>
From that time on I think Andromeda fandom was permanently splintered.  And the unpleasantness caused by that splintering was again very much reflected in the overall tone of the board.<br>
<br>
* What did in your opinion cause the end?<br>
<br>
That's a loaded question!  The answer is in my view, lots of things.  Christian and Lisa were never invested in Andromeda, and so I think their motivation for keeping the place going was not very strong.  I also think that things had gotten to a point where something DID have to give.  The board was so focused on Andromeda and the show was just tanking for so many people, that the angst began to feed on itself.  I think that had the board survived it would have had to be changed so that the focus was not on Andromeda, because it was, in my view, getting to the point of unhealthy.<br>
<br>
Another thing happening was the increasing lack of trust and general unpleasantness and hostility between the membership of the board on the one hand and the administrators and moderators (and Lisa and Chris in particular).  <br>
<br>
I PERSONALLY believe that Lisa and Chris were planning to permanently close Slipstream as early as December of 2002.  But the last straw so to speak happened when person(s) unknown managed to hack into the Slipstream's Officers' Quarters (a private forum supposedly there for the purpose of providing moderators and administrators a place to discuss things like policy and enforcement), and published the entire contents all over the internet.  Well the cat was out of the bag, and whatever you think about the hack (I think it was reprehensible myself), what was revealed was pretty eye openning and hurtful.  Rather than a private place to discuss policy and enforcement, the OQ had become a private place to bash.  I'm not just talking about venting.  I'm talking about systematic, vitriolic, vicious attacks by people on members.  This is bad enough.  The particularly painful thing for me is that I found that I was on the receiving end of these attacks, from people who were quite friendly to me on the board.  One thing is to say more strongly about someone in private what you've already expressed in public.  Another thing is to play nice with someone while you are secretly laughing at and bashing them behind their back.<br>
<br>
And Lisa was in my opinion one of the worst offenders.  Indeed, I frankly think that, but for her presence, things might not have gotten to the point they did in OQ, but that is just an opinion. <br>
 <br>
The irony is that meaningful discussions between members who had been hurt and some of the mods were actually starting to take place at Slipstream when Lisa pulled the rug out from it.  I can only speculate to her motivation but, based on my own interactions with her (on the board, in chat, and via email) for the better part of two years, she couldn't handle getting caught having done something wrong.  In all the time I've known her she has NEVER once admitted that she was wrong.  I think, and again this is just an opinion, that rather than face the music she preferred to pull the plug, and that is precisely what she did.<br>
<br>
* What do you personally think of these events?<br>
<br>
Bottom line is that I think the community has demonstrated a remarkable resilience.  Robert Hewitt Wolfe very kindly provided his board as a temporary way station while people got busy building new places.  The members pulled together to archive Slipstream during the one week grace period of read only time it was given before disappearing forever and, despite the enormity of the task and the inadequacy of time, it got done.<br>
Former slipstreamers have taken up residence at vibrant internet communities like Slipstream Underground and Ex Isle. And, like I said before, something needed to change.  It's just a real shame that it was handled in the way it was handled.  In my view, Lisa and Christian have done more to damage their own good name and reputations in the internet community than any hack or any words I or anyone else could say have done.  But, it's their bed, I hope they enjoy lying in it.<br>
<br>
One thing I remain VERY concerned about is the fact that Christian asked for MONETARY contributions for his new software.  Many Slipstreamers made contributions and they didn't get the benefit of their bargain.  <br>
<br>
* Did you donate money for Slipstream when Christian asked for it a year ago?<br>
No I did not.  But a lot of my friends did.<br>
<br>
* Would you have donated more if that would have prevented Lisa from deleting Slipstream?<br>
I think ego and power trips were a much bigger cause of SS's death than money.  But no I would not have. <br>
 <br>
* Were you involved with saving the threads? And what do you think of the idea to save them as an archive?<br>
Yes I was involved and I think an archive is a great idea.<br>
<br>
* Do you think with the deletion of Slipstream the community died as well? <br>
I believe I answered that one above but no I don't.  I think we're better off without Lisa and Chris and I for one am taking great joy in thumbing my nose at their attempts to destroy this wonderful community.<br>
<br>
Lil <br>
